[Student "S"]
{Sometimes bidding is easy. Partner has 20 or 21 points, balanced. You have 13 points, balanced. Total = 33 or 34 points, balanced. So you close your eyes and bid 6NT.

The contract would be 6NT played by West.

East plays 6NT. South leads the \D10. Too bad South didn't lead a \S. Oh, well.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 4 : \C = 4 :: Total = 11

There is no way to get more than 4 winners in each minor suit, so you need to win either the \SJ or \HQ.

Which one should you try? 

Why not try both? If you make sure you try them in the right order you can have both chances. 

Suppose you lead a small \S from dummy and play your \SJ, and it loses to South's \SQ. If you then try leading a small \H toward dummy's \HQ, obviously the defender with the \HK will grab it to set the contract.

Instead, try the effect of leading toward the \HQ first. If South has the \HK then you will succeed in creating the extra winner you need. But what if you play the \HQ and North takes it with his \HK? Too bad, but at least you are not dead yet. You still have a chance to finesse  North for the \SQ.

Here is an important principle. There are two critical cards, the \SQ and the \HK. However they are not the same degree of criticality.

If the \SQ is in a favorable position, (with North), you are always going to make your contract no matter which you try first.

But if only the \HK is in a favorable position, (with South), you can make the contract only if you try \Hs first.}
